<subSubSection id="C66929DD339D4EE3DCAD88C757F1582D" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="2" pageNumber="75" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="14C3590E2A608BFC45728D13A2DBFB29" pageId="2" pageNumber="75">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB1999B91AB837B8DC2BF8E10E20B889" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="2" pageNumber="75">
<taxonomicName id="D99720EA1C2A1A2860840DB3B7BF66CF" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="2" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
was described from the Mediterranean Sea by 
<bibRefCitation id="660CCCD97287F8FB50D93C25EA68DD26" author="Ledoyer, M" journalOrPublisher="Tethys" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="67 - 81" title="Contribution a l'etude de l'ecologie de la faune vagile profonde de la Mediterranee nord-occidentale. II: Les cumaces (Crustacea)." volume="11" year="1983">Ledoyer (1983)</bibRefCitation>
, who identified the main diagnostic characteristics of the adult male (the flagellum of antenna 2 extending only to the end of thorax and two pairs of pleopods). Ledoyer also noted the difficulty of distinguishing the females of this species from those of two nearby species, 
<taxonomicName id="D7DC4E672966D0866879B846B6EB1BEB" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Hemilamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemilamprops normani" order="Cumacea" pageId="2" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="normani">Hemilamprops normani</taxonomicName>
Bonnier, 1896 and 
<taxonomicName id="F9DDDB9FB0C393147E6225920154F211" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Hemilamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemilamprops cristatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristatus">
<pageBreakToken id="972DD85A2FDCAB97C972677856C3FC54" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" start="start">Hemilamprops</pageBreakToken>
cristatus
</taxonomicName>
(Sars, 1870). Nevertheless, a detailed comparative study of the telson and uropod structures has allowed us to establish the main differences. In 
<taxonomicName id="37FF21ED8342C0A3CF09E37220F51B40" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
the telson has only 3-4 pairs of lateral setae (Fig. 1A); it is shorter than in 
<taxonomicName id="E353EAF21B1774C38121C1BA0C7BBD13" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Hemilamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemilamprops" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hemilamprops</taxonomicName>
, and the terminal setae scarcely reach the distal end of the uropod peduncle; the central terminal seta is longer than the remaining two. Moreover, during the same developmental stage, 
<taxonomicName id="0AA954202E86211D50D8F98CB6B2986A" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
remains smaller than 
<taxonomicName id="04AA2F38F96FC7713A7035FCF860B4C5" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Hemilamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemilamprops normani" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="normani">Hemilamprops normani</taxonomicName>
,based on measurements takenin preadult females (carapace length: 1.13 vs 1.93 mm).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BBBB9909F943B8650FC4E0656210DDE3" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="759157855E16AB27862CDD66BF1FDEED" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D8AC28EB24E94365CCDDC977B47A2277" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="94D17101901F429BB0B1C211D0149455" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
was for a long time considered an endemic Mediterranean species until 
<bibRefCitation id="5372F16DF330E1AC9272086A9E0DE242" author="Shalla, SH" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="1191 - 1200" title="Lampropidae (Crustacea: Cumacea) from the deep north-east Atlantic and the North Sea, with two new species of Hemilamprops and Mesolamprops." url="10.1017/S0025315407055063" volume="87" year="2007">Shalla and Bishop (2007)</bibRefCitation>
reported the presence of this species in the Faeroe-Shetland Channel. In addition, 
<bibRefCitation id="D50A7A1606880FD7B48F0AC498907860" author="Elizalde, M" journalOrPublisher="Publicaciones Especiales del Instituto Espanol de Oceanografia" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="247 - 258" title="Las comunidades suprabentonicas batiales del golfo de Vizcaya (margen sur del canon de Cap-Ferret): composicion faunistica y estructura." volume="11" year="1993">Elizalde et al. (1993)</bibRefCitation>
recorded an undetermined 
<taxonomicName id="606EBE9E38A09401A542A1500761D689" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mesolamprops</taxonomicName>
species from the Bay of Biscay, and recently a study of this same material confirmed that this specimens belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="E916BDF1B1464D4BCA398BAA24251B6E" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
(Corbera and Sorbe in prep.). In the Mediterranean Sea, 
<taxonomicName id="915368E6FC1D100552A07BE01855E297" class="Malacostraca" family="Lampropidae" genus="Mesolamprops" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesolamprops denticulatus" order="Cumacea" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="denticulatus">Mesolamprops denticulatus</taxonomicName>
is distributed between depths of 170 and 570 m (
<bibRefCitation id="6D7D74F68F4EDBEC14AF3C13A9EFD22C" author="Ledoyer, M" journalOrPublisher="Tethys" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="67 - 81" title="Contribution a l'etude de l'ecologie de la faune vagile profonde de la Mediterranee nord-occidentale. II: Les cumaces (Crustacea)." volume="11" year="1983">Ledoyer 1983</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="AD148805A37068C61BA0BBACABD47596" author="Ledoyer, M" journalOrPublisher="Mesogee" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="59 - 70" title="Les Cumaces mediterranees profonds (Crustacea) des campagnes Biomedes I et II et Balgim. Synthese de la distribution bathyale du groupe en Mediterranee occidentale." volume="47" year="1987">1987</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8ED62A3F119F4649EB23112386DF41F5" author="Cartes, J" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biology" pageId="9" pageNumber="82" pagination="745 - 758" title="Local changes in the composition and community structure of suprabenthic peracarid crustaceans on the bathyal Mediterranean: influence of environmental factors." url="10.1007/s00227-003-1090-z" volume="143" year="2003">Cartes et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
), which is a bathymetric distribution pattern similar to that the observed in the Faeroe-Shetland Channel (259-753 m), as well as in the Bay of Biscay (346-708 m).
</paragraph>
